    "content": "# TypeScript Best Practices for Modern Development\n\nTypeScript has become essential for building large-scale JavaScript applications. Here are the best practices to follow.\n\n## Strict Configuration\n\nAlways enable strict mode in your `tsconfig.json`:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"compilerOptions\": {\n    \"strict\": true,\n    \"noImplicitAny\": true,\n    \"strictNullChecks\": true,\n    \"strictFunctionTypes\": true\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## Type Definitions\n\n### Interface vs Type\n\nUse interfaces for object shapes that might be extended:\n\n```typescript\ninterface User {\n  id: string;\n  name: string;\n  email: string;\n}\n\ninterface AdminUser extends User {\n  permissions: string[];\n}\n```\n\nUse type aliases for unions, primitives, and computed types:\n\n```typescript\ntype Status = 'loading' | 'success' | 'error';\ntype UserKeys = keyof User;\ntype PartialUser = Partial<User>;\n```\n\n## Generic Types\n\nCreate reusable, type-safe functions:\n\n```typescript\nfunction createApiResponse<T>(data: T, success: boolean): ApiResponse<T> {\n  return {\n    data,\n    success,\n    timestamp: new Date().toISOString()\n  };\n}\n\ninterface ApiResponse<T> {\n  data: T;\n  success: boolean;\n  timestamp: string;\n}\n```\n\n## Utility Types\n\nLeverage TypeScript's built-in utility types:\n\n```typescript\ninterface User {\n  id: string;\n  name: string;\n  email: string;\n  password: string;\n}\n\n// Pick specific properties\ntype PublicUser = Pick<User, 'id' | 'name' | 'email'>;\n\n// Omit sensitive properties\ntype SafeUser = Omit<User, 'password'>;\n\n// Make all properties optional\ntype UserUpdate = Partial<User>;\n\n// Make specific properties required\ntype UserCreation = Required<Pick<User, 'name' | 'email'>>;\n```\n\n## Discriminated Unions\n\nHandle different states type-safely:\n\n```typescript\ntype LoadingState = {\n  status: 'loading';\n};\n\ntype SuccessState = {\n  status: 'success';\n  data: any[];\n};\n\ntype ErrorState = {\n  status: 'error';\n  error: string;\n};\n\ntype AppState = LoadingState | SuccessState | ErrorState;\n\nfunction handleState(state: AppState) {\n  switch (state.status) {\n    case 'loading':\n      return <Spinner />;\n    case 'success':\n      return <DataList data={state.data} />;\n    case 'error':\n      return <ErrorMessage error={state.error} />;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## Type Guards\n\nCreate runtime type checking:\n\n```typescript\nfunction isString(value: unknown): value is string {\n  return typeof value === 'string';\n}\n\nfunction isUser(obj: any): obj is User {\n  return obj && \n         typeof obj.id === 'string' &&\n         typeof obj.name === 'string' &&\n         typeof obj.email === 'string';\n}\n\n// Usage\nfunction processData(data: unknown) {\n  if (isUser(data)) {\n    // TypeScript knows data is User type here\n    console.log(data.name);\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## Error Handling\n\nUse Result types for better error handling:\n\n```typescript\ntype Result<T, E = Error> = \n  | { success: true; data: T }\n  | { success: false; error: E };\n\nasync function fetchUser(id: string): Promise<Result<User>> {\n  try {\n    const user = await api.getUser(id);\n    return { success: true, data: user };\n  } catch (error) {\n    return { success: false, error: error as Error };\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## Conclusion\n\nFollowing these TypeScript best practices will help you write more maintainable, type-safe code. Remember to leverage the type system to catch errors at compile time rather than runtime.",
